1) Why CO₂ drives the urge to breathe

It’s not carbon itself—it’s what CO₂ does in water (your blood).

When CO₂ builds up, it reacts like this:

CO₂ + H₂O ⇌ H₂CO₃ ⇌ H⁺ + HCO₃⁻

	•	CO₂ + water → carbonic acid (H₂CO₃)
	•	which releases H⁺ (protons)

More H⁺ = lower pH (more acidic)

Your brainstem (chemoreceptors in the medulla) is extremely sensitive to that pH shift. So:

CO₂ ↑ → H⁺ ↑ → pH ↓ → “BREATHE NOW”

That burning/panic feeling is largely your body detecting acidity, not “no oxygen.”

